description: From Middle English *inbreken, from Old English inbrecan (“to break into”), equivalent to in- +‎ break. Cognate with Dutch inbreken (“to break in”), German einbrechen (“to break in”).

entries.meaning: A sudden violent inroad or incursion; an irruption.

verbs.description: inbreak (third-person singular simple present inbreaks, present participle inbreaking, simple past inbroke, past participle inbroken)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To break in; break into; make an incursion into; insert into; interrupt.
examples: Its role is various: to make a claim on, to encounter, to confront, to shake, to inbreak, to erupt, to disrupt, and to disclose.
